title: For Sale/Trade:  SITES Spectre-HC 40 CAL Luger
postcontent:
This auction is for a very rare SITES Spectre HC Semi-Automatic  40 CAL  pistol.  This gun functions excellent, bore is clean, and finish is good to very good.

At just a little over 14 inches in length, this exceptional firearm is even more difficult to find than its rare 9mm version.  Because of its larger caliper, it came originally with a 22 round clip (which is included).  To this date, I have not found another 40 CAL that is currently being sold or has been sold as this one.

The Spectre is an Italian submachine gun that was produced by the SITES factory in Turin. It was designed by Roberto Teppa and Claudio Gritti in the mid-1980s. Production in Italy ceased in the year 1997, with the closure of SITES, but proceeded in very small numbers in Switzerland through Greco Sport S.A., a company founded by one of the designers of the Spectre, Claudio Gritti, until 2001. During the mid 80’s and early 90’s, a limited number made its way to the states via imported by American Arms Inc.  The Spectre is used by the Swiss armed forces and by Italian armed forces, and has been exported elsewhere.

The Spectre is a compact and light weapon, designed for instant firepower in close combat at short ranges. The four models have top-folding buttstocks, and were available with or without a forward handgrip ahead of the magazine housing. The largely polymer Spectre has a stamped-steel receiver.

The Spectre is a standard blowback firearm operating from a closed bolt; however it has some unusual features. The barrel shroud completely hides the barrel. The bolt is designed to pump air through the barrel shroud to provide additional cooling. The Spectre is hammer-fired and the trigger group is double action with a decocker. This allows the shooter to safely carry a round in the chamber and fire immediately. As this eliminates the need for cocking prior to shooting no manual safety is provided. Unconventional 22-round capacity, four-column magazine ise provided with the Spectre, but it can also use conventional magazines.

I’m open to offers and trades, but I am only entertaining trades for either an AR-15 or Bushmaster.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Remington Model 51 Semi-Auto Handgun, 1918-1921
postcontent:
Hello, I have a very rare, antique Remington Model 51 semi-automatic pistol in .380 caliber.  It has been in my family for many years but, due to some financial circumstances, I find myself forced to sell.  I'm not an expert in such matters, but I'd rate the gun approx. 85% in finish and 95% in function (I've only had it to the range a small handful of times in 10 years and have had three failure-to-eject using cheap ball ammo).  There is some wear shown on the outside of the gun on the slide, but overall it's in fantastic shape for its age.  It is being sold with one original magazine.

Below is a link containing a lot of information on the particular model (including fun facts like General Patton used to carry one in WWII).  As per the standards described on the site, the gun was manufactured between 1918-1921 and would make an excellent piece for a collector.  The same model listed on Gunbroker without reserves are priced between $650-$1100, but I am asking $600 to hopefully facilitate a quick sale and not a lot of lowballing.  I would be willing to entertain a partial trade for a subcompact in .380 or 9mm (Ruger LCP, Kel-Tec, etc) but I will need $300 cash at minimum in addition.  I know there are some people out there that like to email and offer 50% of the asking price-- if this is you, please save both of us the trouble and don't do it.  I do have some things I need to take care of, but I will not just give the gun away.

Please don't hesitate to email me with any questions, specific picture requests, etc.  If, for some reason, I cannot get the pictures to load on the ad I'll be happy to email them to you.

Thanks a lot!

http://unblinkingeye.com/Guns/Rem51/rem51.html

title: For Sale:  Polish Tantal AK-74
postcontent:
I'm selling a Century built Polish Tantal chambered in 5.45x39.  I bought the rifle new and have fired 120 rounds through it.  Century Tantals are not built with scope rails however I had a gunsmith weld one on.  The original ill-functioning thumb safety has been replaced with a standard AK safety.  The rifle comes with two mags, the scope carrier, a standard stock, detachable muzzle brake, Tapco trigger-group, and a collapse-able wire stock.  Scope is not included.

This is not one of the Century Tantals with the junk American-made barrels that can't properly stabilize 7N6.  I fired exactly 120 rounds through the gun.  The first 20 shots were fired one at a time, with cleaning in between shots to properly brake in the new barrel.  The next 80 were fired in rapid succession to get the barrel good and hot.  The final 20 were fired at 100 yards to test accuracy.  There were absolutely no failures or keyholes.  I fired the rifle from a sitting position without sandbags.  My groups were under 3".  

All 7N6 ammo is corrosive.  I cleaned the entire rifle over the course of about 45 minutes using various stages of boiling water, wire brushing, Hopepe's 9, Bore Butter patches, and tooth-brushing.  Afterwords, every metal part was treated with a fine layer of oil.  

This is a very nice rifle and the addition of a scope rail gives the 5.45x39 due justice.  The only minor issue is the typical Century lackluster finish.  You don't need to take my word for the reliability of the rifle.  Come to my land in Mukwonago and shoot it yourself.  If you don't want the scope carrier or the wire stock, I'll sell it without.  I might consider trades.  Email me with any questions.

Practically new Bushy XM15E2; its the '14M4IZ' version with the 14.5" M4 profile barrel with the permanenty attached 'Izzy' flash suppressor. VERY low round count (less than 150) and no problems. Heck, it ain't even broke in yet.  I like the 14.5" barreled ARs because they seem to be 'handier' than the 16" versions, and some of the issues that 16" guns have with pressure in the gas system and the bolt cycling too fast are drastically reduced by not having that extra 1.5" of barrel past the gas port. Standard stuff...14.5" barrel w/Izzy comp (brings it up to a BATFE-happy 16"), 1:9 twist, chrome lined bore & chamber, flattop receiver w/ handle, 6 pos collapsible stock, 1 - 30rd mag, factory hard sided case, papers, etc.

title: For Sale:  Win. Model 70 XTR Featherweight -- .270 Win. -- Weaver V9
postcontent:
I am offering for sale a very nice Winchester Model 70 XTR Featherweight in .270 Win. caliber. The rifle is in VERY nice condition as you will see in the photos. There are a few minor surface blemishes on the wood. The metal is almost perfect -- bluing is blemished on one spot on left side of barrel at muzzle. Included are Leupold two-piece bases and rings and a Weaver V9 (3-9X) scope with adjustable objective. The scope is in very nice condition and has fine crosshairs. I acquired this rifle in a trade a few months back. I took it to the range and was amazed how it shot using basic Federal ammo -- in simple terms, three shots covered with a quarter at 100 yds.

I tried to serial number date this rifle and found some interesting info. I am not sure if it affects the value or not. The serial no. is G176XXXX. According to this article http://www.wisnersinc.com/additional_info/Winchesterpost_64_M70.htm "USRAC (United States Repeating Arms Corp.) was formed and continued manufacturing Winchester brand rifles and shotguns under license from Olin Corp. on 7-20-1981. This final year of Olin production saw a new "XTR Featherweight". But very few actually made it to the dealers shelves before USRAC took over. The only way I have been able to discern the difference is that the thin red/brown rubber Pachmayr buttplate would have been the only difference displaying either the name 'Winchester' or 'USRAC'." The butt plate on this rifle says "Winchester."

Photos are available at: http://s698.photobucket.com/albums/vv345/cjkostic/Winchester%20Model%2070%20XTR%20Featherweight

Cash is king, but trade offers are welcome. I will listen to most any offer, but am looking for a Jewel AR tigger, a 28 ga MEC reloader, Encore frame, Encore custom wood, and/or Encore custom barrels.
